<item ID="1774965090" Creator="Robert Hamrick" proto="Markdown" >
<attribute name="Created" >2026-03-31T06:51:29-07:00</attribute>
<attribute name="DominantLanguage" >en</attribute>
<attribute name="Height" >3</attribute>
<attribute name="Modified" >2026-04-05T06:04:39-07:00</attribute>
<attribute name="Name" >2.2 Business problems solved with machine learning</attribute>
<attribute name="Sentiment" >-0.5136363747</attribute>
<attribute name="Sentiments" >-0.8;-0.4;-0.4;0.2;-0.6;-0.4;-0.4;-0.8;-1;-0.8;-0.6;-0.2;-0.6;0;-0.8;-0.6;-0.6;-0.2;-0.8;-0.6;-0.8;0;-0.6;-0.4;-0.8;0;-0.6;-0.6;-0.6;-0.4;-0.4;-0.8;0.2;-0.8;0;-0.6;-0.2;-0.6;-0.8;-0.8;0;-1;-0.8;-0.8</attribute>
<attribute name="Width" >5</attribute>
<attribute name="Xpos" >45</attribute>
<attribute name="Ypos" >0</attribute>
<text >Examples:
* spam filter
* product recommendations
* detecting fraud
* facial detection
* analogies in x rays

Types of machine learning:
* supervised learning: model uses known inputs and outputs to generate future outputs (most problems)
* unsupervised learning: model finds patterns in data without help
* reinforcement learning: interacts with environment and learns to take actions that will maximize rewards

Type of ML will guide you toward appropriate algorithms.

Supervised learning:
* widely applicable
* types of problems: classification; regression
* classification
    * binary classification: fraudulent vs not fraudulent
    * multi class classification: 3 or more categories, e.g. different customer support departments.
* regression: map input to a continuous value like an integer, e.g. predicting stock price

computer vision uses classification

Unsupervised learning: machine creates labels, predicts emerging properties of dataset, constructs patterns from properties 
* clustering: group data into clusters of similar features, e.g. identify groups of customers
    * examples: product recommendations, customer segmentation, targeted marketing, medical diagnostics
* dimensionality reduction
    * examples: visualization, NLP, data structure discovery, gene sequencing

Reinforcement learning: continuously improve model by mining feedback from previous iterations, through trial and error
* best when desired outcome is known, but path to achieving it is not known.
* agent actions in environment receive more rewards and fewer penalties
* example: AWS DeepRacer
    * agent: virtual car
    * environment: virtual race track
    * actions: throttle, steering inputs
    * goal: completing race as quickly as possible without deviating from the track
    * car learns desired guiding behavior to complete the track
        * actions receive more rewards and fewer penalties
* example: self-driving vehicles
    * tasks: continuous detection of the environment; forecasting changes
        * detecting objects, localizing and predicting movement of detected objects
        * outputs of findings act as inputs to systems that make decisions on what they should do with decisions on what to do with vehicle’s controls

Machine learning is appropriate with:
* large datasets, large number of variables
* uncertain of business logic or procedures to accomplish a task
* can be complex: infrastructure, management, technical expertise
* most problems are supervised learning problems
</text>
