<attribute name="Modified" >2026-03-31T06:53:07-07:00</attribute>
<attribute name="Name" >3. Implementing a Machine Learning pipeline with Amazon SageMaker</attribute>
<attribute name="Width" >5</attribute>
<attribute name="Xpos" >45</attribute>
<attribute name="Ypos" >0</attribute>
<item ID="1774965219" Creator="Robert Hamrick" proto="Markdown" >
<attribute name="Created" >2026-03-31T06:53:38-07:00</attribute>
<attribute name="DominantLanguage" >en</attribute>
<attribute name="Height" >3</attribute>
<attribute name="Modified" >2026-04-09T09:35:04-07:00</attribute>
<attribute name="Name" >3.1 Formulating machine learning problems</attribute>
<attribute name="Sentiment" >-0.5103448398</attribute>
<attribute name="Sentiments" >-0.8;-0.8;-0.6;-0.6;-0.4;-0.8;-0.8;-1;-0.6;-0.6;-0.2;-0.8;-0.6;-0.4;-0.8;-0.8;-0.2;-0.6;-0.8;0;-0.4;0.2;-0.2;-0.6;-0.6;-0.6;-0.6;0.2;0</attribute>
<attribute name="Width" >5</attribute>
<attribute name="Xpos" >50.5</attribute>
<attribute name="Ypos" >0</attribute>
<text >Machine learning pipeline

Problem formulation:
* Convert business problem to ML problem: why (what defines success)? can it be measured?
* What kind of ML problem: classification (does the target belong to a class?) or regression (can you predict a numerical value?)

How should you frame the problem?
* Is the problem a machine learning problem?
* Is the problem supervised or unsupervised?  labeled data to train a supervised model?
* What is the target to predict?
* Do you have access to the data?
* What is the minimum performance?
* How would you solve this problem manually?
* What’s the simplest solution?

Example: 
* problem: identify fraudulent credit card transactions so you can stop the transaction before it processes.
* intended outcome: reduce the number of customers who end their membership because of fraud
* define success: move from qualitative statements to quantitative statements that can be measured

What output do you want to see from your model?
* output: transaction is fraudulent or not fraudulent

Use historical data with binary classification.

Example: based on the composition of wine, can you predict the quality and therefore the price?
* view statistics, deal with outliers, scale numerical data

Example: can you use a car’s attributes to predict whether the car will be purchased?
* view statistics
* because data is text-based: encode categorical data by converting text values into numbers

Example: based on the biomechanical features, can you predict whether a patient has an abnormality (disk hernia or spindylolisthesis)
* view statistics
* encode categorical data
* train and tune a model


</text>
