<attribute name="NLNames" >Pearson</attribute>
<attribute name="Name" >3.4 Feature engineering: cleaning your data; dealing with outliers and selecting features</attribute>
<attribute name="Sentiment" >-0.2548387159</attribute>
<attribute name="Sentiments" >0.8;0;0.4;-0.6;-0.4;0.4;0.2;0.6;0.2;0.2;-0.8;-1;-0.6;-0.6;-0.8;0.2;-0.8;-0.4;-0.8;-0.8;-0.4;-0.4;-0.2;-0.6;-0.4;-0.6;-1;-0.8;-0.4;-0.8;-0.6;-0.2;0;-0.4;-0.4;-0.6;0.8;0.4;0.2;-0.6;-0.2;-0.8;0.8;0.8;-0.6;-0.6;-0.2;-0.8;0.2;-0.6;-0.2;-1;-0.6;-0.6;-0.6;0.4;0.4;0.8;-0.2;0;-0.2;-0.4</attribute>
<attribute name="Width" >5</attribute>
<attribute name="Xpos" >67</attribute>
<attribute name="Ypos" >0</attribute>
<text >What is feature engineering?
* feature selection
    * select relevant features, discard rest
    * limit number of features to help prevent overfitting
* feature extraction
    * reformatting, combining, transforming primary features into new ones
    * new dataset that can be use by model to achieve goals
    * range of activities:  invalid values, wrong formats, misspelling, duplicates, consistency, rescale, encode categories, remove outliers, reassign outliers, bucketing, decomposition, aggregation, combination, transformation, normalization, dimensionality reduction

Convert categorical data to numerical values.
* if categorical data has order (low, medium, high), use numeric values that capture ordinal relationship (1, 2, 3)
* if categorical data has no order, break into multiple columns with 0 and 1 values in order to avoid introducing an ordinal relationship to the data

### Cleaning data

* variations in strings (“medium” vs “med”):  convert to standard text
* variations in scale (car doors vs cars purchased):  normalize to common scale
* columns with multiple data types (combine safety and maintenance):  parse into multiple columns
* missing data:  delete rows or impute (replace) data
* outliers

Imputing missing data:
1. determine why data is missing
2. impute
    * univariate:  add data for single row
    * multivariate:  add data for multiple rows
    * usually replaced with mean or median, but there are other methods

### Outliers

Outliers are points in data set that lie at an abnormal distance from other values.
* Don’t always want to clean up because add richness to data set.  * But can make harder to make accurate predictions because they skew values away from other, more normal values related to feature.
* Might indicate that data belongs to another column.

Types of outliers:
* univariate: abnormal values for a single variable
* multivariate: abnormal values for two or more variables

Finding outliers:
* box plot: variation and distance from the mean.  box has values within two quartiles of the mean.
* scatter plot

Common approaches to outliers:
* delete the outlier:  if based on artificial error
* transform the outlier:  take natural log of value to reduce variation caused by extreme outlier value and thereby reduce the outlier’s influence on the overall data set
* impute a new value for the outlier:  use the mean of the feature if caused by artificial error

Feature selection:
* filter method: use statistical method to measure the relevance of features by their correlation with the target variable
    * faster, cheaper because no training involved
* wrapper method:  how useful is a subset of a feature?
    * train model on feature and measure how successful the model is
    * risk of overfitting
* embedded method
    * algorithm-specific
    * might use a combination of filters and wrappers

Filter methods use a proxy method to capture measure instead of actual model’s performance.
* Pearson’s correlation coefficient: measures statistical relationship  (association) between two continuous variables
* Linear discriminant analysis (LDA): find a linear combination of features that separates two or more classes
* Analysis of variance (ANOVA): analyze differences among group means in a sample
* Chi-square:  single number that tells you the difference between observed counts and counts you expect if there were absolutely no relationships in the population
* These are general methods, not tuned to model or problem.

Wrapper methods use a predictive model to score feature subsets.  * Each new subset is used to train a model, which is tested on a holdout set.
* The score for the subset is counted by counting the number of mistakes made on the holdout set or the error rate of the model.
* Provide best-performing feature set for the particular model or problem.
* Forward selection starts with no features and adds them until the best model is found.
* Backward selection starts with all features, drops them one at a time, and then selects the best model.

Embedded methods combine filter and wrapper methods.
* implemented by algorithms that have their own feature selection methods
* decision trees
* LASSO and RIDGE regression (have built-in penalization algorithms to reduce overfitting)</text>
