<attribute name="Ypos" >0</attribute>
<text >Many SageMaker algorithms support training data in csv.
* no header record
* target variable in first column

Most algorithms work best when using Protobuff recordIO format.
* take advantage of “pipe mode” to stream data directly from S3

Holdout method: split data into multiple sets
* 10% testing (features, no labels)
* 10% validation (features, labels)
* 80% training (features, labels)

K-fold cross validation:  randomly partition data into K segments
* use data outside of segment for training
* validate with segment
* test with K different models

Data in specific order can lead to biases.
* randomize data before training
* with smaller sets, can be useful to use stratified sampling to ensure that training and test data have approximately the same percentage of samples of each target class as the complete set
* use train-test-split function from sklearn

Training models with Amazon SageMaker: use containers behind the scenes
* prebuilt containers include Apache MXNet, TensorFlow, PyTorch, Chainer
* support for ML libraries: scikit-learn, SparkML

Built-in algorithms:
* for supervised learning: XGBoost, Linear Learner for lassification and Quantitative (or regression) problems
* factorization machines to address recommendation and time series prediction problems
* for unsupervised learning: K-means clustering, Principal Component Analysis (PCA) to solve problems like identifying customer groupings based on customer behavior
* specialized libraries for processing images or other deep learning tasks

**XGBoost** (Extreme Gradient Boosting): implementation of gradient boosted trees algorithm
* supervised learning algorithm that attempts to predict target variable by combining estimates from a set of simpler, weaker models
* handles various data types, relationships, distributions.  Large number of hyperparameters can be tweaked and tuned.
* good for problems in regressions, classification, and ranking

**SageMaker Linear Learner**: provides solution for classification and regression problems
* simultaneously explore different training objectives and choose the best solution from your validation set
* large number of models, select the best for your needs
* provides increase in speed over naive hyperparameter optimization techniques

**K-means**: unsupervised learning algorithm that attempts to find groupings in data where members are as similar as possible to one another and as different as possible from members of other groups
* you define the algorithm for determining similarity

Creating a training job in SageMaker
* url of S3 bucket for training data
* url of S3 bucket for job output
* ECR path where training code is stored
* compute resources to use for model training (ml compute instance types)
</text>
