<item ID="1774965272" Creator="Robert Hamrick" proto="Markdown" >
<attribute name="Created" >2026-03-31T06:54:31-07:00</attribute>
<attribute name="DominantLanguage" >en</attribute>
<attribute name="Height" >3</attribute>
<attribute name="Modified" >2026-04-14T14:53:44-07:00</attribute>
<attribute name="NLOrganizations" >SageMaker SDK</attribute>
<attribute name="Name" >3.6 Hosting and using the model</attribute>
<attribute name="Sentiment" >-0.4956521845</attribute>
<attribute name="Sentiments" >-0.6;-0.8;-0.8;-0.4;-0.8;-0.8;-0.2;-0.6;0.2;-0.6;-0.8;-0.2;0.2;-0.4;-0.8;-0.8;-0.4;0.6;-0.6;-0.8;-0.6;-0.8;-0.6</attribute>
<attribute name="Width" >5</attribute>
<attribute name="Xpos" >78</attribute>
<attribute name="Ypos" >0</attribute>
<text >Deploy trained model using SageMaker.
The goal is to generate predictions for client applications.

Two deployment options:
* for single predictions, deploy with SageMaker hosting services
    * multiple instances behind a load-balanced endpoint
    * applications call api endpoint to make predictions
* for predictions for an entire dataset, use SageMaker batch transform
    * perform predictions for entire dataset
    * store results in S3
    * shuts down, terminates compute instances
    * useful for performing batch predictions when you test the model:  run entire validation set against the model without writing any code to process and collate the individual results

Goal of deployment:  provide a managed environment to host models, provide inference securely and with low latency

Deployment is continuous

After deployment, monitor production data and retrain model if necessary.
Newly deployed models need to reflect current production data.

To deploy, specify instance type, minimum and maximum number of instances.

Create endpoint: use console or SageMaker SDK.  Or create multi-model endpoint support to save resources when you have multiple models to deploy.

Obtaining predictions:  
* when deploying ML models to make predictions on new data, apply the same data processing steps that were used in training to each inference request.  otherwise, can get incorrect prediction results.
* by using inference pipelines, can reuse the data processing steps from model training during inference without maintaining two separate copies of the same code.
* inference pipelines are managed.  when deploy pipeline model, the service installs and runs the same containers on each EC2 instance in the endpoint or each batch transform job
* the sequence of feature processing and inference runs with low latency because the containers are located on the same EC2 instances





</text>
