<attribute name="Name" >3.7 Evaluating the accuracy of the model: calculating classification metrics; selecting classification thresholds</attribute>
<attribute name="Sentiment" >-0.5540983699</attribute>
<attribute name="Sentiments" >-1;-0.4;-0.6;-0.2;-0.2;-0.6;-0.6;0;-0.8;-0.6;-0.8;-1;0;0.4;0;-0.8;-0.8;-0.2;-0.6;-0.8;-0.8;-0.8;-0.4;-0.6;-0.8;-0.8;-0.8;-0.4;-1;-0.4;-1;-0.8;-0.6;-1;-0.6;-0.6;-0.4;-0.8;-0.4;-0.6;-0.8;-1;-1;0;0;-0.8;-0.6;-0.6;0.2;-1;-1;-1;0.2;-1;-0.6;-0.6;-0.4;-0.6;-0.4;0.8;-0.4</attribute>
<attribute name="Width" >5</attribute>
<attribute name="Xpos" >83.5</attribute>
<attribute name="Ypos" >0</attribute>
<text >Type of ML problem will influence the model you choose.
* classification
* regression

Example: simple binary classification problem where an image recognition model labels data as ‘cat’ or ‘not cat’.
* compare predicted values to actual values
* put values in a confusion matrix
    * true positive: predicted true, actual true
    * false positive: predicted true, actual false
    * true negative: predicted false, actual false
    * false negative: predicted false, actual true
* evaluate accuracy:  Is the business goal to identify as many cats as possible (and not concerned about false positives)?  Or is it to identify animals that are not cats?  (How many false negatives can you tolerate?)
    * **sensitivity**: percentage of positive identifications
        * TP/(TP+FN), where TP+FN is total number of cats
    * **specificity** (also known as selectivity, true negative rate): percentage of negatives correctly identified 
        * TN/TN+FP, where TN+FP is total number of ‘not cats’, i.e. actual negatives

### Calculating classification metrics

Model 1: confusion matrix

| --- |
| | actual cats | actual not cats |
| predicted cats | TP: 107 | FP: 23 |
| predicted not cats | FN: 69 | TN: 42 |

Model 2: confusion matrix

| --- |
| | actual cats | actual not cats |
| predicted cats | TP: 148 | FP: 53 |
| predicted not cats | FN: 28 | TN: 12 |

Sensitivity

```
= \frac{\textrm{TP}}{\textrm{TP + FN}}  \label{TP+FN is total number of positives}
```

Specificity

```
= \frac{TN}{TN + FP}  \label{TN+FP is total number of negatives}
```

Model 1 sensitivity:  percentage of cats identified as cats.

```
= \frac{107}{107 + 69} = 0.6079
```

Model 1 specificity:  percentage of not cats correctly identified as not cats.

```
= \frac{42}{42 + 23} = 0.6461
```


### Selecting classification thresholds

Models return probabilities:  if [predicted] &gt;= threshold: is a cat; if [predicted] &lt; threshold: is not a cat.

You can change the threshold to change the predictions.

Visualize with a Receiver Operating Characteristics (ROC) graph.
It summarizes all the confusion matrices that each threshold produced.
* Calculate sensitivity (true positive rate) against specificity (false positive rate).  (Calculate false positive rate by subtracting specificity from 1.)
* (1, 1) means that have correctly identified all cats and incorrectly identified all not cats. (This is bad.)
* (c, c) the proportion of correctly identified samples is the same as the proportion of incorrectly identified samples
* goal is usually high sensitivity, low specificity (low false positive): so better if line between threshold rates is toward the top left corner

Can plot ROC curve for each model, but you do quick comparisons with “Area Under the Curve Receiver Operator Curve” (AUC-ROC) graphs.
* when area under curve is higher, model is better at predicting cats as cats and not cats as not cats.

Other metrics

Accuracy (also, “Model’s score”): add correct predictions, divide by total number of predictions

```
= \frac{ \textrm{TP} + \textrm{TN}}{\textrm{TP} + \textrm{TN} + \textrm{FP} + \textrm{FN}}
```

Accuracy is not as effective when there are many true negatives in data set, since model may be better at predicting “not cats.”
* for credit card company identifying fraud cases, need very high rates of predicting true positives, more than true negatives.

Precision: proportion of positive results that were correctly classified (removes the negative predictions).  Good if cost of false positives is high.

F1 score:  combines precision and sensitivity.

```
= 2 \frac{\textrm{precision} \cdot \textrm{sensitivity}}{\textrm{precision} + \textrm{sensitivity}}
```

Use when have a class imbalance but want to preserve the equality between precision and sensitivity.

Mean squared error (MSE):  for regression problems.  Take model’s prediction and compare model’s prediction to actual outcome.
* take difference between prediction and actual value
* square the difference
* sum all the squared differences for all observations

```
= \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i = 1}^{n} (y_i - \tilde{y}_i)^2
```

### ML tuning process

