<item ID="1774965289" Creator="Robert Hamrick" proto="Markdown" >
<attribute name="Created" >2026-03-31T06:54:48-07:00</attribute>
<attribute name="DominantLanguage" >en</attribute>
<attribute name="Height" >3</attribute>
<attribute name="Modified" >2026-04-19T13:38:35-07:00</attribute>
<attribute name="NLNames" >Adam;Xavier</attribute>
<attribute name="NLOrganizations" >AUC</attribute>
<attribute name="Name" >3.8 Hyperparameter and model tuning</attribute>
<attribute name="Sentiment" >-0.1411764775</attribute>
<attribute name="Sentiments" >-0.6;-0.6;-0.6;0.8;-0.6;-0.4;-0.6;0.6;-0.2;-0.6;0;-0.4;-0.4;-0.6;0.4;-0.6;-0.2;0.6;-0.8;1;0.8;-0.8;1;-1;-0.2;-0.6;-0.6;-0.8;0;0.8;0.4;1;-0.6;-0.4</attribute>
<attribute name="Width" >5</attribute>
<attribute name="Xpos" >89</attribute>
<attribute name="Ypos" >0</attribute>
<text >Hyperparameters are the knobs that tune the ML algorithm to improve its performance.

Types of hyperparameters:
* model:  help define model
    * example: neural network for a computer vision problem: additional attributes of the architecture need to be defined: filter size, pooling, stride, padding
* optimizer:  relate to how the model learns patterns based on data.
    * used for neural network model
    * optimizers: gradient descent, stochastic gradient descent
    * optimizers that include momentum:  Adam
    * optimizers that initialize parameter weights with methods like Xavier initialization or He initialization
* data:  related to attributes of the data itself
    * includes attributes that define different data augmentation techniques like cropping or resizing for image-related problems
    * often used used when you don’t have enough data or enough variation in your data

Tuning hyperparameters can be labor intensive.
* traditionally done manually by someone with domain experience:  select hyperparameters based on intuition and experience.  The train model and score it on validation data.  And repeat.
* automated tuning:  find best version of model by running multiple training jobs on data set using algorithms and hyperparameter ranges you specify.  The chooses hyper parameters in a model that performs the best as measured by a metric that you choose.  Gaussian process regression predicts which hyper parameter values might be most effective at improving fit.  Bayesian optimization to balance exploring the hyperparameter space and exploiting specific hyperparameter values when appropriate.

Example:  binary classification problem on fraud data set.
* Goal is to maximize area under AUC curve metric of the algorithm by training a linear learning algorithm model.
* You don’t know what values of learning rate, beta1, beta2, and epoxy should be used to train the best model.
* To find best values of hyperparameters, specify ranges of values that SageMaker hyperparameter tuning will search.  Will find the combination of values that performs the best by the objective metric that you choose.
* in example, return training job with highest AUC

Hyperparameter tuning doesn’t necessarily improve the model.

Best practices:
* don’t adjust every hyperparameter
* limit range of values to what’s most effective
* run one training job at a time instead of multiple in parallel
* in distributed training jobs, make sure the objective metric that you want is the one reported back
* with SageMaker, converge log-scaled hyperparameters to linear-scaled when possible

SageMaker Autopilot
* create a job that specifies the test, training, and target.
* Autopilot analyzes the data, selects appropriate features, and then trains and tunes the models
* documents the metrics and find the best model based on the provided data
* results include winning model and metrics, jupyter notebook you can use to investigate the results
* doesn’t automate date preprocessing, but can save time on feature selection and model tuning
</text>
