<item ID="1776825451" Creator="Robert Hamrick" proto="Markdown" >
<attribute name="Created" >2026-04-21T19:37:30-07:00</attribute>
<attribute name="DominantLanguage" >en</attribute>
<attribute name="Height" >3</attribute>
<attribute name="Modified" >2026-04-22T20:16:07-07:00</attribute>
<attribute name="Name" >4.2 Processing time series data</attribute>
<attribute name="Sentiment" >-0.5428571524</attribute>
<attribute name="Sentiments" >-0.8;-0.8;-0.6;-0.8;-0.6;-0.6;-0.4;-1;-0.6;-0.6;-1;-0.6;0.4;-0.4;-1;0;-1;-0.4;0.2;-0.8;0</attribute>
<attribute name="Width" >5</attribute>
<attribute name="Xpos" >60.5</attribute>
<attribute name="Ypos" >0</attribute>
<text >Time series data:  

tends to be correlated:  dependency between data points

dealing with regression problem.  regression assumes that the data points are independent.

develop method for dependency

add related data to augment forecasting model.  For example, to make a prediction about retail sales, could include information about product being sold such as item identification or sale price.  along with units sold per time period.

third, metadata.  like brand name for product, genre for music to group results

working with multiple data sources, different or incomplete time stamps

might be able to infer missing data:  do times sequence?
local time or UTC?

Missing values in raw data.  for example, out of stock -&gt; 0 sales.  but if forecast generated based on 0 sales values, forecast will be incorrect.  (i.e. demand doesn’t equal sales on those days)

Calculating missing data:
* Forward Fill:  last known value == missing value
* Moving Average:  avg(previous known values) == missing value
* Backward Fill (lookahead):  next value == missing value.  Avoid this because it uses the future for the past.
* Interpolation:  equation: linear spline polynomial
* zero fill:  (often used in retail because missing sales data shouldn’t be calculated)

Downsampling:  moving from a finer grained time to a less finely grained time.
If have sales data with exact times but inventory data by day.  Downsampling:  sum sales data by day.

Upsampling:  move from less finely grained time to a more finely grained time.  Extremely difficult.

Outliers:  removing outlines is known as smoothing.  can create a better model.  but maybe model is expecting noisy data, could compromise model.
</text>
