<item ID="1776825464" Creator="Robert Hamrick" proto="Markdown" >
<attribute name="Created" >2026-04-21T19:37:43-07:00</attribute>
<attribute name="DominantLanguage" >en</attribute>
<attribute name="Height" >3</attribute>
<attribute name="Modified" >2026-04-22T20:16:09-07:00</attribute>
<attribute name="NLOrganizations" >Amazon</attribute>
<attribute name="Name" >4.2.1 Special considerations for time series data</attribute>
<attribute name="Sentiment" >-0.08333333085</attribute>
<attribute name="Sentiments" >-0.2;0.4;-1;-1;0.2;0;0.8;-0.4;-0.6;-0.4;0.6;0.6</attribute>
<attribute name="Width" >5</attribute>
<attribute name="Xpos" >66</attribute>
<attribute name="Ypos" >0</attribute>
<text >Seasonality:  repeating where frequency is stable.  sales higher at the end of a quarter and in the fourth quarter.

Stability, Stationarity:  informs how much system’s past behavior informs future behavior.  A system with low stability won’t be successful at predicting the future.

Trend for time series?  If adjust series for the trend, it can be difficult to compare it with another series that was also adjusted for the trend.  If trends dominate values in series, could lead to overestimates and correlation between two series.

Autocorrelation:  a form of noise because separate observations aren’t independent of each other.  A time series with autocorrelation might overstate the accuracy of the model it has produced.  Some modules can help correct for autocorrelation.

Choose an appropriate algorithm.  Determined by type of data set and features of data set.

Amazon forecast supports:
* Autoregressive Integrated Moving Average (ARIMA):  removes autocorrelations that can influence the pattern of observations
* DeepAR+
* Exponential Smoothing (ETS):  useful for datasets with seasonality
* Non-Parametric Time Series (NPTS)
* Prophet</text>
