<item ID="1776825482" Creator="Robert Hamrick" proto="Markdown" >
<attribute name="Created" >2026-04-21T19:38:01-07:00</attribute>
<attribute name="DominantLanguage" >en</attribute>
<attribute name="Height" >3</attribute>
<attribute name="Modified" >2026-04-22T21:14:34-07:00</attribute>
<attribute name="NLOrganizations" >Amazon;Amazon Forecast</attribute>
<attribute name="Name" >4.3 Using Amazon Forecast</attribute>
<attribute name="Sentiment" >-0.4066666767</attribute>
<attribute name="Sentiments" >0.2;0.4;-0.8;0.4;0.6;-0.8;0.2;-0.8;0.4;-0.6;-0.8;-0.4;-1;0;0.8;0;-0.4;0;-0.6;0;-0.4;-0.4;-0.6;0;-0.4;0.2;-0.8;-0.8;-0.2;-0.6;0.2;-0.6;-0.8;-0.6;0.8;-0.8;-0.6;-0.6;-0.6;-0.4;-0.6;-0.6;-0.6;-0.6;-0.6;-0.8;-0.6;-0.8;-0.8;-0.8;-0.8;-0.6;-1;-0.6;-0.6;-0.2;-0.6;-0.8;-0.4;-0.8</attribute>
<attribute name="Width" >5</attribute>
<attribute name="Xpos" >71.5</attribute>
<attribute name="Ypos" >0</attribute>
<text >Import as much data as you have, both historical data and related data.

Do basic evaluation and feature engineering before you use the data to train a model.

To train a predictor, you need to choose an algorithm.  Amazon Forecast can choose for you if you select “AutoML.”

Select domain for your data.  If you’re not sure what is the best fit, can select a custom domain.  Domains require specific types of data.

When you have a trained model, you can use the model to make a forecast using an input dataset group.

After you’ve generated the forecast, you can query the forecast.  You can export it to a bucket in Amazon S3.  And you can encrypt the data in the forecast before exporting it.

Overall process for working with Forecast:
* import historical and related data
* Forecast inspects the data, identifies key data, and selects an appropriate algorithm.
* Forecast uses the algorithm to train and optimize a custom model and produce a predictor.
* create forecasts by applying the predictor to your dataset
* retrieve forecasts in the AWS management console or export as csv
* use api and aws cli commands to create and retrieve forecasts

Select a domain to improve the efficiency of the predictor.  Each domain has specific types of data to apply when you build the predictor.

Supported domains:
* retail
* inventory planning
* EC2 capacity
* work force
* web traffic
* metrics
* custom

For example, retail domain expects data for item identifiers, a timestamp for the observation, the number of sales for that item, specified timestamp.

For a retail forecast:
* time series data: transactions sales data; timestamp, item, quantity
* metadata: category, item color, item id to link back to time series data.  metadata typically doesn’t change.
* related data: sales price, other promotion data; timestamp and item id to link back to data

For a web traffic forecast:
* time series data: web page id; page view per month; timestamp
* related and metadata:  page category (navigation, content category); geographic identifier for web client.

Forecasters
* use an algorithm to train the model
* use the model to make a forecast using input dataset group

Forecast divides data into training and test data.  Time series data can’t be divided into random samples.  Can specify multiple back test windows to spit the data multiple times, train the model, and use metrics to determine which model gives the best results.

You can change how Forecast splits the data by setting the back test window offset parameter when you create the predictor.  The default is 1.

After you’ve trained the model, you need to measure its accuracy.
Evaluation metrics:
* weighted quantile loss (wQuantileLoss)
* root mean square error (RMSE)

weighted quantile loss (wQuantileLoss):
* provides probabilistic predictions at three distinct quantiles: 10%, 50%, 90%.
* shows how much uncertainty is associated with each forecast
* P10 quantile predicts that 10% of the time, the true value will be less than the predicted value
    * suppose that you’re a retailer forecasting product demand for winter gloves that sell well only during the fall or winter.  you don’t have sufficient storage space and the cost of invested capital is high.  you might use the P10 quantiles to order a relatively low number of winter gloves.  the P10 forecast overestimates the demand for winter gloves only 10% of the time.  so you’ll be sold out of winter gloves 90% of the time.
* a P50 quantile predicts that 50% of the time the true value will be less than the predicted value.
    * if you know that there is a moderate demand for gloves and you aren’t concerned about being overstocked, you might choose to use the P50 quantiles to order gloves.
* a P90 quantile predicts that 90% of the time the true value will be less than the predicted value.
    * if you determine that being understocked on gloves will result in lost revenue, you might chose the P90 quantile to order gloves
* calculate weighted quantile loss:  how far off the forecast a certain quantile is from actual demand in either direction
* lower wQuantileLoss metrics mean that forecasts are more reliable

Root mean square error (RMSE):  the square of all errors
also calculates how far off the forecasted values were from the actual test data
* RMSE finds the difference between the actual target value in the dataset and the forecasted value for that time period
* squares the differences
* good for forecast validity when errors are mostly of the same size (not many outliers)
* lower RMSE means model’s forecasts are more reliable

Example: web retail using accuracy metrics to evaluate a forecast.  The retailer wants to predict the demand for sales of a particular brand of shoes.
* predictor provides a forecasted demand of 1000 with P10, P50, and P90 values: &lt;880, &lt;1050, &lt;1200.
* base decision on risk of not being able to fulfill orders or that they’ll have excess inventory</text>
