<item ID="1776308605" Creator="Robert Hamrick" >
<attribute name="Created" >2026-04-15T20:03:24-07:00</attribute>
<attribute name="DominantLanguage" >en</attribute>
<attribute name="Modified" >2026-04-15T20:03:40-07:00</attribute>
<attribute name="Name" >Week 3 Updates</attribute>
<attribute name="Sentiment" >-0.3199999988</attribute>
<attribute name="Sentiments" >-0.2;0.6;-0.8;-1;-0.2</attribute>
<attribute name="Xpos" >67.5</attribute>
<attribute name="Ypos" >0</attribute>
<text >Hi everyone!  This week we will be looking at the second part of deploying a predictive model in AWS.  The labs involve creating the model, training it with the data we prepared last week, and measuring its output against ground truth.  We will be looking at common metrics used to calculate &quot;how effective&quot; a model is at its predictions (this is the topic of this week&apos;s discussion post).
Some of the notebooks in this section can take a while to run (up to 15 minutes).   You can see the status of the notebook by checking the lower left corner.  It will say &apos;Busy&apos; or &apos;Idle&apos;.  If you see it showing &apos;Busy&apos; status, that means not all of the cells have finished running so you will not yet see the output.
AWS had kind of a bad week. There were some intermittent errors and login problems, which is why this module is showing up today instead of yesterday.  Since this sort of thing seems to happen more often than either of us would like, I am removing late penalties for labs for the rest of the semester. You can now turn in any lab up to 7 days late with no penalty.
Onward to the next module, and hopefully fewer surprises.
</text>
