<attribute name="Name" >UsingTinderbox</attribute>
<attribute name="Sentiment" >-0.350684942</attribute>
<attribute name="Sentiments" >-0.6;-0.4;-0.6;0.2;-0.4;-0.4;0.4;-0.6;0.6;-0.4;0.8;-0.6;-0.4;-0.6;-0.6;-0.8;-0.6;-0.6;-0.4;-0.8;-0.8;-0.2;-0.2;-0.6;-0.6;-0.6;-0.6;0.6;-0.2;-0.6;-0.6;0.4;0.2;0;-0.8;-0.6;-0.6;-0.6;-0.4;-0.4;1;-0.6;-0.4;-0.6;0.2;-0.4;-0.8;-0.6;-0.4;-0.6;0;0.6;-0.2;-0.6;-0.6;0.8;-0.4;-0.8;-0.2;-0.6;-0.8;-0.6;-0.6;0;-1;-0.4;-0.2;-0.2;-0.6;-0.6;0;-0.6;-0.8</attribute>
<attribute name="Xpos" >0</attribute>
<attribute name="Ypos" >0</attribute>
<text >Here is a partial Tinderbox action syntax reference:

# Overview
Tinderbox actions and queries are composed in a simple language, somewhat resembling C, Java, and Javascript.

# Basic Query Structure
## Comparison Operators
- == (equals): $Name == &quot;exact name&quot;
- != (not equals): $Name != &quot;some name&quot;
- &gt; (greater than): $WordCount &gt; 100
- &lt; (less than): $Created &lt; date(&quot;2024-01-01&quot;)
- &gt;= (greater than or equal): $WordCount &gt;= 50
- &lt;= (less than or equal): $Created &lt;= date(&quot;2024-12-31&quot;)

## String Functions
- .contains(pattern): $Name.contains(&quot;Vienna&quot;) - supports regex patterns
- .icontains(pattern): case-insensitive contains
- .beginsWith(string): $Name.beginsWith(&quot;Dr.&quot;)
- .endsWith(string): $Name.endsWith(&quot;Notes&quot;)
- strings may be compared using any of the comparison operators.

## Date Functions
- date(string) constructs a date from a text representation
- dates may be compared using any of the comparison operators

## Logical Operators
- &amp; (AND): $WordCount &gt; 100 &amp; $Name.contains(&quot;Vienna&quot;)
- | (OR): $Name.contains(&quot;Gödel&quot;) | $Name.contains(&quot;Neurath&quot;)
- ! (NOT): !$Name.contains(&quot;test&quot;)

## Collection/Relationship Queries
- $ChildCount: number of child notes
- $DescendantCount: total descendant count
- $Name(parent): parent container name
                                                
## Numeric Attributes
- $WordCount: word count of note text
- $Xpos, $Ypos: location in map vuew
- $Height, $Width: size in map view
- $OutlineOrder: position in the outline
- many numeric operators are available: cos(x),sin(x),sqrt(x)

## Link Information
- $OutboundLinkCount: number of outbound links
- $InboundLinkCount: number of inbound links
- linkedTo(/path/to/note[,linktype]): true if this note is linked to the target note
- linkedFrom(/path/to/note[,linktype])`: true if this note is linked from the target note
- createLink(/path/source,/path/destination[,linkType]): create a link

## Notable Attributes
- $Name: note title
- $Text: note content
- $Created: creation date
- $Modified: last modified date
- $Container: path of parent container. Set new value to move notes.
- $Prototype: assigned prototype (see Inheritance below)
- $Path: the hierarchical /path/to/a/note

- An action may refer to the attributes of other notes: $Text(/path/to/note)
- Designators describe notes relative to `this` note: $Name(parent).
- Common designators: parent, nextSibling, child, all, and find(*query*)
- Designators also refer to groups of notes: $Color(children) or $Created(ancestors)
                                                
## User Attributes
Attribute names begin with a letter, usually capitalized, and cannot contain punctuation or whitespace.

`createAttribute(attributeName,attributeType)` creates a new attribute. attributeType may be one of ”boolean, number, string, color, date, interval, list, set, dictionary”.
                                                                                             
## Examples
- Find long notes: $WordCount &gt; 500
- Recent notes: $Created&gt; date(&quot;2024-01-01&quot;)
- Notes about Vienna: $Name.contains(&quot;Vienna&quot;) | $Text.contains(&quot;Vienna&quot;)
- Complex: $WordCount &gt; 100 &amp; $Name.contains(&quot;[A-Z]&quot;) &amp; !$Name.contains(&quot;test&quot;)
- Containers with many children: $Children.count() &gt; 10
- Notes modified recently: $Modified &gt; date(&quot;today - 1 month&quot;)

                                        
## Inheritance
Notes can have a *Prototype* note. Any note can be a prototype, though by convention prototype notes
set $IsPrototype to true. If a note has a prototype, it *inherits* values from the prototype note unless
the note has its own values. Notes can always override inherited values.  Prototypes can themselves have
prototypes.

## Tips
- Use regex patterns in .contains() for advanced matching
- Combine multiple conditions with &amp; and |
- Use parentheses for complex logic: (A | B) &amp; C
- Date comparisons require date() function for literals
    
</text>
</item>
<item ID="1774963440" Creator="Robert Hamrick" >
<attribute name="Created" >2026-03-31T06:23:29-07:00</attribute>
<attribute name="DominantLanguage" >en</attribute>
<attribute name="Modified" >2026-03-31T06:23:29-07:00</attribute>
<attribute name="NLOrganizations" >HTML</attribute>
<attribute name="Name" >Poster Notes</attribute>
<attribute name="Sentiment" >-0.4571428682</attribute>
<attribute name="Sentiments" >0.8;-0.6;-0.8;-0.8;-0.4;-0.8;-0.6</attribute>
<attribute name="Xpos" >4.5</attribute>
<attribute name="Ypos" >0</attribute>
<text >In Tinderbox a **poster** note is a note that, in map view, displays a web view on its face.  

The poster note typically adopts the Poster prototype, which the user can add if it is not already installed.

The HTML displayed by the poster is computed from a **template note**. Template notes are often kept in /Templates. Templates are HTML, and can incorporate information from Tinderbox. For example, `^value($ScreenWidth)` returns the width of the poster in pixels, and `^value($ScreenHeight)` returns the height. `^text` returns the text of the poster note.  

The name of the template to be used is stored in the attribute $PosterTemplate.

Tinderbox note dimensions in the map view are determined by $Width and $Height. These are measured in screen units; typically, 1 screen unit is 32px.

Visualizations from plotly, mermaid, chart.js and other sources have worked well.
</text>
</item>
</item>
<item ID="1774963441" Creator="Robert Hamrick" >
<attribute name="Created" >2026-03-31T06:23:29-07:00</attribute>
<attribute name="DominantLanguage" >en</attribute>
<attribute name="Modified" >2026-03-31T06:23:29-07:00</attribute>
<attribute name="NLNames" >Claude Code</attribute>
<attribute name="Name" >Notes</attribute>
<attribute name="Sentiment" >-0.3500000052</attribute>
<attribute name="Sentiments" >-0.2;-0.4;-0.8;0</attribute>
<attribute name="Xpos" >9</attribute>
<attribute name="Ypos" >0</attribute>
<text >This container holds notes that Claude Code makes for future reference. Notes are organized into topical catalog containers. Each catalog&apos;s $Text briefly describes when its contents are relevant.

At session start, query the immediate children of this container to read catalog descriptions. Drill into catalogs that are relevant to the current session. Do not load all catalogs — only fetch detail you need.

When adding notes, place them in an appropriate existing catalog. If no catalog fits, create a new one with a concise description of when its contents matter. Keep notes concise.
</text>
</item>
</item>
